SIMPLE: pr_munire
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Præmunire
<hw>Pr⟦ae⟧m`u*ni"re</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Corrupted
from L. <ets>praemonere</ets> to forewarn, cite. See
<er>Admonish</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The
offense of introducing foreign authority into England, the penalties for
which were originally intended to depress the civil power of the pope in
the kingdom.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The writ grounded on that
offense.</def> <au>Wharton.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The penalty ascribed
for the offense of <xex>pr⟦ae⟧munire</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wolsey incurred a <qex>pr⟦ae⟧munire</qex>, and forfeited his
honor, estate, and life.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The penalties of <xex>pr⟦ae⟧munire</xex> were
subsequently applied to many other offenses; but prosecutions upon a
<xex>pr⟦ae⟧munire</xex> are at this day unheard of in the English
courts.</note> <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Praemunire</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Præmunire
<hw>Pr⟦ae⟧m`u*ni"re</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To subject
to the penalties of pr⟦ae⟧munire.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>T.
Ward.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Praemunitory</ent>⟦br⟧
